"Stap L., Lourens L.J., Thomas E., Sluijs A., Bohaty S., Zachos J.C.","High-resolution deep-sea carbon and oxygen isotope records of Eocene Thermal Maximum 2 and H2",2010,"Geology","38","7",,"607","610",,,10.1130/G30777.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77956020991&partnerID=40&md5=a654d9c8f724472127d6334d1efdb927","Faculty of Geosciences, Utrecht University, 3584 CD Utrecht, Netherlands; Department of Geology and Geophysics, Yale University, New Haven, CT 06520, United States; Department of Earth and Environmental Sciences, Wesleyan University, Middletown, CT 06459, United States; Biomarine Sciences, Institute of Environmental Biology, Utrecht University, 3584 CD Utrecht, Netherlands; School of Ocean and Earth Science, National Oceanography Centre, University Road, Southampton SO17 1BJ, United Kingdom; Earth and Planetary Sciences, University of California, Santa Cruz, CA 95064, United States","Stap, L., Faculty of Geosciences, Utrecht University, 3584 CD Utrecht, Netherlands; Lourens, L.J., Faculty of Geosciences, Utrecht University, 3584 CD Utrecht, Netherlands; Thomas, E., Department of Geology and Geophysics, Yale University, New Haven, CT 06520, United States, Department of Earth and Environmental Sciences, Wesleyan University, Middletown, CT 06459, United States; Sluijs, A., Biomarine Sciences, Institute of Environmental Biology, Utrecht University, 3584 CD Utrecht, Netherlands; Bohaty, S., School of Ocean and Earth Science, National Oceanography Centre, University Road, Southampton SO17 1BJ, United Kingdom; Zachos, J.C., Earth and Planetary Sciences, University of California, Santa Cruz, CA 95064, United States","Eocene Thermal Maximum 2 (ETM2) and H2 were two short-lived global warming events that occurred ~2 m.y. after the Paleocene-Eocene thermal maximum (PETM, ca. 56 Ma). We have generated benthic foraminiferal stable carbon and oxygen isotope records of four sites along a depth transect on Walvis Ridge (~3.5-1.5 km paleodepth, southeast Atlantic Ocean) and one site on Maud Rise (Weddell Sea) to constrain the pattern and magnitude of their carbon isotope excursions (CIEs) and deep-sea warming. At all sites, ETM2 is characterized by ~3 °C warming and a-1.4‰ CIE. The H2 event that occurred ~100 k.y. later is associated with ~2 °C warming and a-0.8‰ CIE. The magnitudes of the δ13C and δ18O excursions of both events are significantly smaller than those during the PETM, but their coherent relation indicates that the δ13C change of the exogenic carbon pool was similarly related to warming during these events, despite the much more gradual and transitioned onset of ETM2 and H2. © 2010 Geological Society of America.",,"Atlantic Ocean; Carbon isotopes; Carbon pool; High resolution; Oxygen isotope records; Paleocene-eocene thermal maximums; Stable carbon; Thermal maxima; Weddell Sea; Global warming; Oceanography; Oxygen; Isotopes; benthic foraminifera; carbon isotope; Eocene; global warming; Hypsithermal; oxygen isotope; Paleocene; paleoclimate; stable isotope; Atlantic Ocean; Maud Rise; Southern Ocean; Walvis Ridge; Weddell Sea",,,,,,"Bemis, B.E., Spero, H.J., Bijma, J., Lea, D.W., Reevaluation of the oxygen isotopic composition of planktonic foraminifera: Experimental results and revised paleotemperature equations (1998) Paleoceanography, 13, pp. 150-160. , doi: 10.1029/98PA00070; Bijl, P.K., Schouten, S., Sluijs, A., Reichart, G.-J., Zachos, J.C., Brinkhuis, H., Early Palaeogene temperature evolution of the southwest Pacific Ocean (2009) Nature, 461, pp. 776-779. , doi: 10.1038/nature08399; Cramer, B.S., Wright, J.D., Kent, D.V., Aubry, M.-P., Orbital climate forcing of δ13C excursions in the late Paleocene-early Eocene (chrons C24n-C25n) (2003) Paleoceanography, 18, p. 1097. , doi: 10.1029/2003PA000909; Dickens, G.R., O'Neil, J.R., Rea, D.K., Owen, R.M., Dissociation of oceanic methane hydrate as a cause of the carbon isotope excursion at the end of the Paleocene (1995) Paleoceanography, 10, pp. 965-971. , doi: 10.1029/95PA02087; Emanuel, K., A simple model of multiple climate regimes (2002) Journal of Geophysical Research (Atmospheres), 107, p. 4077. , doi: 10.1029/2001JD001002; John, C.M., Bohaty, S.M., Zachos, J.C., Sluijs, A., Gibbs, S.J., Brinkhuis, H., Bralower, T.J., North American continental margin records of the Paleocene-Eocene thermal maximum: Implications for global carbon and hydrological cycling (2008) Paleoceanography, 23, pp. PA2217. , doi: 10.1029/2007PA001465; Kennett, J.P., Stott, L.D., Abrupt deep-sea warming, palaeoceanographic changes and benthic extinctions at the end of the Paleocene (1991) Nature, 353, pp. 225-229. , doi: 10.1038/353225a0; Kurtz, A.C., Kump, L.R., Arthur, M.A., Zachos, J.C., Paytan, A., Early Cenozoic decoupling of the global carbon and sulfur cycles (2003) Paleoceanography, 18, p. 1090. , doi: 10.1029/2003PA000908; Lisiecki, L.E., Lisiecki, P.A., Application of dynamic programming to the correlation of paleoclimate records (2002) Paleoceanography, 17, p. 1049. , doi: 10.1029/2001PA000733; Lourens, L.J., Sluijs, A., Kroon, D., Zachos, J.C., Thomas, E., Röhl, U., Bowles, J., Raffi, I., Astronomical pacing of late Palaeocene to early Eocene global warming events (2005) Nature, 435, pp. 1083-1087. , doi: 10.1038/nature03814; McCarren, H., Thomas, E., Hasegawa, T., Röhl, U., Zachos, J.C., Depth dependency of the Paleocene-Eocene carbon isotope excursion: Paired benthic and terrestrial biomarker records (Ocean Drilling Program Leg 208, Walvis Ridge) (2008) Geochemistry, Geophysics, Geosystems, 9, pp. Q10008. , doi: 10.1029/2008GC002116; Nicolo, M.J., Dickens, G.R., Hollis, C.J., Zachos, J.C., Multiple early Eocene hyperthermals: Their sedimentary expression on the New Zealand continental margin and in the deep sea (2007) Geology, 35, pp. 699-702. , doi: 10.1130/G23648A.1; Ridgwell, A., Interpreting transient carbonate compensation depth changes by marine sediment core modeling (2007) Paleoceanography, 22, pp. PA4102. , doi: 